\begin_layout Standard
A scatterplot or Scatter diagram shows the relationship between two quantitative variables measured for the same individuals.
 The values of one variable appear on the horizontal axis,
 and the values of the other variable appear on the vertical axis.
 Each individual in the data appears as a point on the graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An important component to a scatterplot is the form of the relationship between the two variables.
 i.e.
 whether it is linear or curvilinear or nonlinear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another important component to a scatterplot is the strength of the relationship between the two variables.
 The slope provides information on the strength of the relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The strongest linear relationship occurs when the slope is 1.
 This means that when one variable increases by one,
 the other variable also increases by the same amount.
 This line is at a 45 degree angle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The strength of the relationship between two variables is a crucial piece of information.
 Relying on the interpretation of a scatterplot is too subjective.
 More precise evidence is needed,
 and this evidence is obtained by computing a coefficient that measures the strength of the relationship under investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A scatterplot displays the strength,
 direction,
 and form of the relationship between two quantitative variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A correlation coefficient measures the strength of that relationship
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlation r measures the strength of the linear relationship between two quantitative variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pearson r is 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum\frac{(x_{i}-\bar{x})(y_{i}-\bar{y)}}{s_{x}*s_{y}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 r is always a number between -1 and 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 r > 0 indicates a positive association.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 r < 0 indicates a negative association.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Values of r near 0 indicate a very weak linear relationship.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 The strength of the linear relationship increases as r moves away from 0 toward -1 or 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 The extreme values r = -1 and r = 1 occur only in the case of a perfect linear relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size large
Simple Linear Regression
\size default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear regression analysis is used to predict the value of a variable based on the value of another variable.
 The variable we want to predict is called the dependent variable.
 The variable we are using to predict the other variable's value is called the independent variable.
 We are interested here to study mainly the cause effect relationship between two variables (in this case year and production).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is only one independent feature,
 it is known as Simple Linear Regression,
 and when there are more than one feature,
 it is known as Multiple Linear Regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 when there is only one dependent variable,
 it is considered Univariate Linear Regression,
 while when there are more than one dependent variables,
 it is known as Multivariate Regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simplest form of linear regression,
 and it involves only one independent variable and one dependent variable.
 The equation for simple linear regression is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y=b_{0}+b_{1}x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* y is the dependent variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* x is the independent variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* b0 is the intercept
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* b1 is the slope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Predictive Power
\series default
:
 Once a linear regression model is fitted to data,
 it can be used to make predictions about the dependent variable based on new values of the independent variable(s).
 For example,
 in this case we have a model related to year and production of rice,
 we can predict production of rice in the different years.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Forecasting:

\series default
 Linear regression is often used in time series analysis to forecast future values based on past trends.
 For example,
 predicting future production,
 stock prices,
 or economic indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Problem of Inference:
 
\series default
We want to know the functional relationship between y and x,
 that is,
 we want an approximation of the true regression of y on x- problem of curve estimation or problem of inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here our objective starts with understanding how the covariate x affects the response y.
 We want to estimate f (the function) but not for predicting y .
 Now fˆ cannot be treated as black-box,
 we need to know its exact mathematical form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
What is the best Fit Line?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our primary objective while using linear regression is to locate the best-fit line,
 which implies that the error between the predicted and actual values should be kept to a minimum.
 There will be the least error in the best-fit line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The best Fit Line equation provides a straight line that represents the relationship between the dependent and independent variables.
 The slope of the line indicates how much the dependent variable changes for a unit change in the independent variable(s).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this we gain a estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 the regression function.
\end_layout

