Cluster Analysis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cluster analysis is an unsupervised learning algorithm for exploratory analysis of data.
 Cluster reffers to groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a body of methodologies that look for natural groupings in a given data set by striving for
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* high intra-group-similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* low inter-group-similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective of cluster analysis is to find similar groups of subjects,
 where the “similarity” between each pair of subjects represents a unique characteristic of the group vs.
 the larger population/sample.
 Strong differentiation between groups is indicated through separate clusters;
 a single cluster indicates extremely homogeneous data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\size normal
Similarity Measures:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The foundation of clustering methods.
 Similarity between two points is defined in terms of the distance between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The smaller the distance between them,
 the more similar they are,
 and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most commonly used distance measure for numeric data:
 the Euclidean distance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here in our report we use the distance matrix as a distance measure.
