\begin_layout Subsection

\size normal
Hierarchical Clustering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methods which partition a data set of size n into the desired number k of clusters.
 Hierarchical clustering is another unsupervised machine learning algorithm,
 which is used to group the unlabeled datasets into a cluster and also known as hierarchical cluster analysis or HCA.,
 by constructing a hierarchy of clusters in one of two ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
AGGLOMERATIVE approach
\shape default
 :
 Starting with n clusters of size 1,
 merge the two most similar clusters to get 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 clusters,
 and repeat this process 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k+1$
\end_inset

 times to get k clusters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
DIVISIVE approach :
 
\shape default
Starting with a single cluster of size n,
 split it into two optimally,
 repeat the process a number of times,
 splitting one of the clusters at each step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We merged/Split the data points till desired number of clusters is obtained,
 or the distance between the two closest clusters exceeds a certain threshold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A convenient means of displaying the results is a dendrogram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agglomerative is a bottom-up approach,
 in which the algorithm starts with taking all data points as single clusters and merging them until one cluster is left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our study we use this approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Generic algorithm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 0
\series default
.
 Form n clusters such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}=\{x_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 and initialize number of clusters k by n.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1
\series default
.Find clusters 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

 which are closest to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 2.Merge Ci ,
 Cj and reduce k by 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 3
\series default
.If k equals the desired number of clusters or if the smallest inter-cluster distance exceeds a given threshold,
 then stop,
 else go to step 1.
\end_layout

